      "side": 1,
      "message": "the relationship between objects are:\n\n```\nHttpClient\n  └─\u003e unordered_map\u003cstring, shared_ptr\u003cConnectionPool\u003e\u003e\n        └─\u003e ConnectionPool\n              └─\u003e vector\u003cshared_ptr\u003cConnectionInfo\u003e\u003e\n                    └─\u003e ConnectionInfo (with async handlers)\n```\n\nThe coredump occurred at:\n```\n  ConnectionInfo::afterRead() - connPolicy-\u003einvalidResp(respCode)\n```\n\nOr, potentionally on the other callbacks (I think I saw this/similar one before [during the dev time - esp. resHandler() part])\n\n```\n- ConnectionInfo::afterRead()   callback(parser-\u003ekeep_alive(), connId, res);\n- ConnectionInfo::waitAndRetry() - callback(false, connId, res);\n- ConnectionInfo::afterSendData() - resHandler(res);\n```\n\n\nThe problem potentially may occur:\n\n- The callback member variable holds a std::function\n  that may capture references to objects in the ConnectionPool or HttpClient.\n\n- If the ConnectionPool or HttpClient is destroyed while async operations are\n  pending, the callback may reference destroyed objects [1][2][3].\n\n- The shared_from_this() pattern keeps ConnectionInfo alive\n  but doesn\u0027t protect objects captured by the callback.\n\nSome links discuss about the similar topics.\n[1] https://stackoverflow.com/questions/26397269/what-if-a-basic-waitable-timer-is-destructed-when-there-are-still-async-operatio\n[2] https://www.boost.org/doc/libs/latest/doc/html/boost_asio/overview/core/cancellation.html\n```\nCancellation requests should not be emitted during an asynchronous operation\u0027s initiating function. Cancellation requests that are emitted before an operation starts have no effect. Similarly, cancellation requests made after completion have no effect.\n```\n[3] https://www.boost.org/doc/libs/latest/doc/html/boost_asio/overview/core/cancellation.html\n\n\nFor example, ConnectionInfo::callback may still be invoked even if its object is destroyed.\n\nIf so, the callback (invalidResp()) from this usage seems invalid.\n\n```\nboost::beast::http::async_read(\n    conn, buffer, thisParser,\n    std::bind_front(\u0026ConnectionInfo::afterRead, this, shared_from_this()));\n```\n\n\nUnfortunately, the problem seems not easily reproducible.\n\nI think it is because the async operation may need to be occurred\nat a very specific timing and pushed into the io_context queue\nduring the object destruction time.\n(I\u0027m not also able to reproduce it).\n\nThe high-level reproduction sequence may look like\n\n- Create a HttpClient (ConnectionPool \u0026 ConnectionInfo).\n- An async operation (e.g. read) is started.\n  (Note: however, it is queued into io_context, but not yet executed)\n\n- HttpClient is destroyed (ConnectionPool/ConnectionInfo also destroyed)\n  and all asyncs are cancelled.\n  The async operation was already in io_context, its callback may still be invoked.\n\nAs the solution, the associated object (e.g. ConnectionInfo)\u0027s lifetime would need\nto be kept as long as the callback is needed.\n(i.e. object is captured and kept as long as io callbacks are needed).\n\n---\nAlthough I haven\u0027t been able to reproduce it at will. what I have done (also making sure the code is good) are:\n\n1) Test by creating a lot connections/destructions (python)\n```\n\n        for i in range(iterations):\n            # Create new session\n            session \u003d requests.Session()\n            session.verify \u003d False\n            \n            # Send request to a slow endpoint or non-existent resource\n            try:\n                # Use a thread to send request\n                def send_request():\n                    try:\n                        session.post(\n                            f\"{self.base_url}/redfish/v1/EventService/Subscriptions\",\n                            json\u003d{\n                                \u0027Destination\u0027: \u0027http://192.0.2.1:8080/events\u0027,\n                                \u0027Protocol\u0027: \u0027Redfish\u0027\n                            },\n                            timeout\u003d30\n                        )\n                    except Exception as e:\n                        pass  # Expected to fail\n                \n                thread \u003d threading.Thread(target\u003dsend_request)\n                thread.daemon \u003d True\n                thread.start()\n                \n                # Destroy session immediately while request is pending\n                time.sleep(0.01)  # 10ms delay\n                session.close()\n                del session\n                    \n            except Exception as e:\n                print(f\"  Error in iteration {i}: {e}\")\n```\n\n2) A standalone program to create \u0026 destroys HttpClients.\n\nSkeleton\n```\n    for (int i \u003d 0; i \u003c iterations; i++)\n    {\n        // Create client\n        auto client \u003d std::make_unique\u003ccrow::HttpClient\u003e(ioc, policy);\n        clientsCreated++;\n\n        boost::beast::http::fields headers;\n        headers.set(boost::beast::http::field::host, \"192.0.2.1\");\n\n        // Send multiple requests to unreachable IPs\n        // These will trigger async resolve operations\n        for (int j \u003d 0; j \u003c 3; j++)\n        {\n            std::string ip \u003d \"192.0.2.\" + std::to_string((i * 3 + j) % 254 + 1);\n            try\n            {\n                client-\u003esendData(\n                    \"test data\",\n                    boost::urls::url_view(\"http://\" + ip + \":8080/test\"),\n                    ensuressl::VerifyCertificate::NoVerify,\n                    headers,\n                    boost::beast::http::verb::post);\n                requestsSent++;\n            }\n            catch (const std::exception\u0026 e)\n            {\n                // Ignore exceptions\n            }\n        }\n\n        // Destroy immediately - async operations still pending\n        client.reset();\n        clientsDestroyed++;\n    }\n```\n\n---\nTo reproduce it, I think - some kind of the low-level delay injection at IO-layer \u0026 boost-code so that the async operations are held on io_context queue during the object destruction, but it seems not easy.\n\n----\nPerhaps, for the future thinking, [2] suggests to use `boost::asio::bind_cancellation_slot()` approach to deal with async cancellation (i.e. timer.cancel() or async call cancel()) properly.\n\n[2] https://www.boost.org/doc/libs/latest/doc/html/boost_asio/overview/core/cancellation.html\n\n----\nUntil then, I think semantically, capturing \u0027object\u0027 as a whole in lambda (instead of passing both `this` \u0026 `shared_ptr` to the function which may later invoke callback) seems more consistent (in making sure the same value).",
